Housing price

by Team Fengkuangxingqisi(group number): Yin Ruan, Zecheng Kong, Jialin Liu, Haocheng Sheng

2025-11-29

##Introduction Housing markets provide a rich context for understanding how structural characteristics, construction history, and neighborhood environments shape property values. The Ames Housing dataset, widely used in statistical learning, offers detailed information on both physical attributes and qualitative assessments of nearly 2900 residential properties.

In this project, we investigate: To what extent do location, structural features, and construction era contribute to variations in house prices? And how reliably can we estimate the effect of key predictorssuch as above-ground living areausing modern modeling and bootstrap techniques?

Using a combination of exploratory analysis, regression modeling, classification, and bootstrap resampling, this study aims to uncover the major drivers of housing prices in Ames, Iowa, and evaluate the stability of these effects.

##Data

The dataset contains 2,919 observations split into train, test and sample_submission.All modelling and analysis in this report is based on the train dataset, which includes the target variable SalePrice. The dataset includes 79 predictor variables, spanning: Structural features: square footage, number of rooms, basement area, garage details Quality ratings: kitchen quality, exterior quality, overall material/finish Location information: neighbourhood, lot configuration, lot frontage Temporal information: year built, remodel year Amenities: fireplaces, pools, porches, misc features

#Missing Data Overview Using summarisation and column-wise NA counting,substantial missingness was found in variables such as Fence (80.7%), Alley (93.8%), MiscFeature (96.3%), PoolQC (99.5%) and FireplaceQu (47.3%).Because high-NA variables often represent absence of a feature rather than missing measurement, we avoided dropping them to prevent information loss.

#Missing Data Treatment We adopted a structured, meaning-based imputation strategy: 1. Feature indicates presence or absence Variables such as Alley, Fence, FireplaceQu, PoolQC, BsmtQual, BsmtCond, GarageType, GarageQual etc. were imputed using category labels like NoAlley, NoFence, NoGarage or NoBsmt. 2. Year built for missing garage year GarageYrBlt NA values were replaced with YearBuilt to maintain chronological consistency. 3. Electrical Only one missing valuereplaced with standard circuit Breakers. 4. LotFrontage (most complex case) Missing values imputed with median rather than 0 to avoid biasing structural interpretation

Descriptive Results (No Controls) We grouped properties by neighbourhood and summarised: number of houses mean price median price Ranking by mean price: Highest: NoRidge Lowest: MeadowV This was further confirmed via boxplots and the Top 10 mean-price neighbourhood bar chart. These descriptive findings already demonstrate large spatial disparities.

Controlling for Structural Variables House prices are influenced by many factors beyond location. Using reference literature (Zooplas 10 Factors That Affect Home Value), and selecting variables available in our dataset, we fitted the model:

Using log-transformed prices ensures normality and stabilises variance. Interpreting Neighbourhood Effects Regression coefficients for each neighbourhood were transformed into percentage effects relative to the baseline category.

Key Finding: Even after controlling for structural and quality characteristics, certain neighbourhoods retain strong price premiums. This confirms that location-based amenities, attractiveness, and socioeconomic factors play roles beyond home characteristics alone.

Grouping Houses by Age We grouped houses into three construction periods: Old: built before 1980 Mid: 19801999 New: 2000 onward Summary statistics show: Mean Price: New > Mid > Old Median Price: same order Thus, newer houses tend to be more expensive.

Controlling for Key Structural Variables

Interpreting results (converted to % effects): Mid houses serve as baseline New: approx. +10% premium Old: approx. 0.37% relative to Mid Therefore, under equal structural conditions: Houses built between 19802000 command the highest relative prices, followed by post-2000 houses, with pre-1980 houses being least valuable.

Supporting Trend Analysis The full time-series plot of average price by construction year shows two peaks: properties from early 1900s (historic homes) properties built post-2000 This explains why age effects are not monotonic.

Defining High vs Low Price We defined: high price: SalePrice > median low price: SalePrice median This produced a balanced binary target variable. We used an 80/20 training-test split with stratification.

Variable Selection The initial attempt using all variables produced warnings:fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred This implied perfect separation driven by variables with extremely dominant categories (e.g., factors where 99% of entries fall in one level). We manually removed these non-informative predictors and retained meaningful, balanced features such as: OverallQual, OverallCond GrLivArea TotalBsmtSF, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtExposure GarageArea,GarageQual LotArea KitchenQual, FullBath, HalfBath ExterQual, ExterCond YearBuilt, YearRemodAdd 1stFlrSF, 2ndFlrSF These were converted to dummy variables via the recipe.

Model Training A logistic regression model (glm engine) was fitted using tidymodels. ROC curve and AUC were computed: AUC = 0.972 This means:When randomly selecting one high-price and one low-price house, the model assigns a higher predicted probability to the high-price house in 97.2% of cases.This reflects exceptionally strong ranking and classification power.

##Discussion & Insights # Neighbourhood MattersEven After Adjusting for Structural Features Neighbourhood remains one of the strongest determinants of price. This suggests that buyers value local amenities, safety, schools, and community characteristics beyond physical house features.

Age and PriceNot a Simple Linear Relationship

Newer homes tend to cost more, but the highest premium occurs for 19802000 homes after adjustments. Very old historic homes show occasional high prices, contributing to wavy longitudinal trends.

Predictive Modelling Shows Strong Potential

The classification model demonstrates that: structural quality variables (OverallQual, KitchenQual, ExterQual) house size (GrLivArea,basement area) and certain key amenities (garage size, bathrooSs) are highly predictive of price class. Such models could support automated valuation tools or decision support systems.

Conclusions

This project provides a comprehensive examination of how neighborhood, structural features, and construction era interact to shape housing prices in Ames, Iowa. Regression models show that both location and quality exert strong effects, while classification models accurately distinguish high-value homes.Bootstrap analysis further confirms the robustness of key predictors, highlighting the reliability of living area as a primary driver of market value.
These findings demonstrate how statistical modeling and resampling techniques can be used to extract meaningful insights from real-estate data and support informed decision-making.
